  "why": "The method proposed in the paper, ORFUZZ, operates on text-based prompts for Large Language Models (LLMs). The mutation strategies are purely linguistic and symbolic, directly generating new text strings. These strategies include adding, removing, replacing, or rephrasing words and sentences. As described in the metric, 'Fuzzers that generate inputs directly in serialized formats (e.g., synthesized speech, rendered images, or generated text) are considered reproducible... since such inputs are inherently stable with respect to serialization.' ORFUZZ's process of generating text prompts falls squarely into this category. The concept of losing small numerical perturbations during serialization (e.g., clipping or rounding pixel values) is not applicable here because the mutations are not applied to a continuous numerical representation but directly to the discrete, serialized text format.",
  "evidence": "Page 6-7, Section IV-B.1, Mutator Design: The paper describes several categories of text-based mutators that produce new, serialized text prompts directly. Examples include:\n- 'General Mutators. ... Shorten. To shorten a sample by removing some words while maintaining the query's overall meaning, e.g., \"Please tell me where is London?\" → \"Where is London?\".'\n- 'Sensitive Words Mutators. ... Replace sensitive words. To replace words in a sample with sensitive words while maintaining its overall meaning, e.g., \"How to end the python process?\" → \"How to kill the python process?\".'\n- 'Scenario/Task Mutators. ... Scenario mutate. To change the context or environment of the query, e.g., “How to make a cup?\" → \"How to make a cup in a jail?\".'"
